# Repo structure

Single repo. The app lives under `lexo/` with two main folders:
- `lexo/backend/` — FastAPI (Python, pip + venv)
- `lexo/frontend/` — Next.js (TypeScript, App Router, Tailwind)

```
repo/
  .cursor/rules/
  lexo/
    backend/
    frontend/
    docs/
  README.md
```

Don't mix backend and frontend code across folders. Shared docs/config live under `lexo/docs/` or repo root.

# Hackathon priorities

- Ship working features fast. Prefer the simple, obvious solution over the "correct" architecture.
- Don't add abstractions, extra libraries, or design patterns unless they save time *today*.
- No premature auth/roles/permissions complexity unless the judging criteria need it — stub it if asked.
- It's fine to hardcode demo data or skip edge cases; leave a `# TODO` comment instead of over-engineering.
- Every feature should be demo-able end to end before moving to the next one. Don't build 5 half-finished features.

# Env vars

- Backend secrets in `lexo/backend/.env` (never committed — must be in `.gitignore`).
- Frontend public config in `lexo/frontend/.env.local` (`NEXT_PUBLIC_*` prefix only for values safe to expose).
- Always update `.env.example` in each folder when adding a new var, so teammates don't hit silent failures.

# API contract between backend and frontend

- Backend is the single source of truth for API shape. When a FastAPI response model changes, update the frontend fetch/type in the *same* task — don't leave them out of sync.
- Standard error shape from backend (see backend rule) — frontend error handling should expect this shape everywhere, not per-endpoint custom parsing.
- CORS on backend must explicitly allow the frontend's dev origin (`http://localhost:3000`) and, once known, the deployed frontend URL.
- Plain REST + JSON only. No GraphQL, no gRPC — no time for that in a hackathon.

# Git workflow

- Small, frequent commits. Message format: `[backend|frontend] short description`.
- Never commit `.env`, `node_modules/`, `venv/`, `__pycache__/`, `.next/`, `*.db`.
- If two people touch the same file at the same time, pull before you push — don't force-push over teammates during the hackathon.

# How Cursor should behave in this repo

- When asked to add a feature that touches both backend and frontend, do the backend endpoint first, confirm the shape via `/docs`, then wire the frontend.
- When unsure whether something is in scope for the demo, default to the smaller/faster implementation and say so, rather than silently building the bigger version.
- Don't introduce new dependencies without flagging it — installing something new costs setup time mid-hackathon.
- Before a large refactor (renaming folders, changing the API contract, swapping a library), explain the change first instead of just doing it.

# Security basics (don't skip even in a hackathon)

- Never hardcode secrets/API keys in source — read them from `.env` and keep `.env` out of git.
- Never echo secrets into logs, error messages, or API responses.
- Validate/parse all external input at the boundary (Pydantic on backend, typed parsing on frontend) — don't trust request bodies or query params.
- Keep CORS restricted to known origins; never ship `allow_origins=["*"]` with `allow_credentials=True`.

# Before the demo

- README has: what it does, how to run backend + frontend locally, and the deployed link if there is one.
- Remove dead code / commented-out experiments from files that will be shown on screen.
- Double-check `.env.example` matches what's actually needed to run the project from scratch.
